ce:section.ce:para:
In photocatalytic processes, the precise control of reactive oxygen species (ROS) offers considerable benefits, especially in attaining both efficient and targeted organic transformations [67]. ROS, such as singlet oxygen (1O2), O2
                     •−, and hydroxyl radicals (·OH), serve as pivotal oxidants in photocatalytic reactions [68]. By meticulously regulating the generation of various ROS, researchers can enhance the efficiency of photocatalysts and improve reaction selectivity, thus reducing undesired side reactions [69]. For example, singlet oxygen, with its exceptional selectivity and gentle oxidative properties, is particularly suited for reactions that necessitate mild oxidation conditions [70]. In contrast, superoxide anions, owing to their potent oxidative strength, provide substantial benefits in scenarios requiring swift reaction kinetics [71]. The capability to fine-tune ROS production allows for the creation of tailored photocatalytic environments suited to diverse organic substrates, facilitating both efficient and selective transformations. Moreover, controlling ROS selectivity can lower excess energy expenditure and enhance the overall efficiency of the reaction. Therefore, the investigation of photocatalysts with selective ROS generation is a highly promising area of research. In this study, we present the identification of a N,P co-doped carbon dots with distinctive structure and photophysical properties. These carbon dots exhibit selective production of superoxide anions and demonstrate remarkable photocatalytic activity, which could be successfully applied to the degradation of boronic acids and the oxidation of N-phenyl tetrahydroisoquinolines, showcasing a broad range of substrate applicability and achieving high yields (Scheme 1
                     ).
